206/** Type of lightmap that is used for primitive components */
207UENUM()
208enum class ELightmapType : uint8
209{
210 /** Use the default based on Mobility: Surface Lightmap for Static components, Volumetric Lightmap for Movable components. */
211 Default,
212 /** Force Surface Lightmap, even if the component moves, which should otherwise change the lighting. This is only supported on components which support surface lightmaps, like static meshes. */
213 ForceSurface,
214 /**
215 * Force Volumetric Lightmaps, even if the component is static and could have supported surface lightmaps.
216 * Volumetric Lightmaps have better directionality and no Lightmap UV seams, but are much lower resolution than Surface Lightmaps and frequently have self-occlusion and leaking problems.
217 * Note: Lightmass currently requires valid lightmap UVs and sufficient lightmap resolution to compute bounce lighting, even though the Volumetric Lightmap will be used at runtime.
218 */
219 ForceVolumetric
220};

223UENUM()

226 /** Take the minimum occlusion value. This is effective for avoiding over-occlusion from multiple methods, but can result in indoors looking too flat. */
227 OCM_Minimum,

229 * Multiply together occlusion values from Distance Field Ambient Occlusion and Screen Space Ambient Occlusion.
230 * This gives a good sense of depth everywhere, but can cause over-occlusion.

232 */
233 OCM_Multiply,
234 OCM_MAX,

310/** Describes how to handle lighting of translucent objets */
311UENUM()
312enum ETranslucencyLightingMode : int
313{
314 /**
315 * Lighting will be calculated for a volume, without directionality. Use this on particle effects like smoke and dust.
316 * This is the cheapest per-pixel lighting method, however the material normal is not taken into account.
317 */
318 TLM_VolumetricNonDirectional UMETA(DisplayName="Volumetric NonDirectional"),
319
320 /**
321 * Lighting will be calculated for a volume, with directionality so that the normal of the material is taken into account.
322 * Note that the default particle tangent space is facing the camera, so enable bGenerateSphericalParticleNormals to get a more useful tangent space.
323 */
324 TLM_VolumetricDirectional UMETA(DisplayName="Volumetric Directional"),
325
326 /**
327 * Same as Volumetric Non Directional, but lighting is only evaluated at vertices so the pixel shader cost is significantly less.
328 * Note that lighting still comes from a volume texture, so it is limited in range. Directional lights become unshadowed in the distance.
329 */
330 TLM_VolumetricPerVertexNonDirectional UMETA(DisplayName="Volumetric PerVertex NonDirectional"),
331
332 /**
333 * Same as Volumetric Directional, but lighting is only evaluated at vertices so the pixel shader cost is significantly less.
334 * Note that lighting still comes from a volume texture, so it is limited in range. Directional lights become unshadowed in the distance.
335 */
336 TLM_VolumetricPerVertexDirectional UMETA(DisplayName="Volumetric PerVertex Directional"),
337
338 /**
339 * Lighting will be calculated for a surface. The light is accumulated in a volume so the result is blurry,
340 * limited distance but the per pixel cost is very low. Use this on translucent surfaces like glass and water.
341 * Only diffuse lighting is supported.
342 */
343 TLM_Surface UMETA(DisplayName="Surface TranslucencyVolume"),
344
345 /**
346 * Lighting will be calculated for a surface. Use this on translucent surfaces like glass and water.
347 * This is implemented with forward shading so specular highlights from local lights are supported, however many deferred-only features are not.
348 * This is the most expensive translucency lighting method as each light's contribution is computed per-pixel.
349 */
350 TLM_SurfacePerPixelLighting UMETA(DisplayName="Surface ForwardShading"),
351
352 TLM_MAX,
353};

355/** Determines how the refraction offset should be computed for the material. */
356UENUM()
357enum ERefractionMode : int
358{
359 /**
360 * By default, when the root node refraction pin is unplugged, relies on the material IOR evaluated from F0.
361 * Refraction is computed based on the camera vector entering a medium whose index of refraction is defined by the Refraction material input.
362 * The new medium's surface is defined by the material's normal. With this mode, a flat plane seen from the side will have a constant refraction offset.
363 * This is a physical model of refraction but causes reading outside the scene color texture so is a poor fit for large refractive surfaces like water.
364 */
365 RM_IndexOfRefraction UMETA(DisplayName="Index Of Refraction"),
366
367 /**
368 * By default, when the root node refraction pin is unplugged, no refraction will appear.
369 * The refraction offset into Scene Color is computed based on the difference between the per-pixel normal and the per-vertex normal.
370 * With this mode, a material whose normal is the default (0, 0, 1) will never cause any refraction. This mode is only valid with tangent space normals.
371 * The refraction material input scales the offset, although a value of 1.0 maps to no refraction, and a value of 2 maps to a scale of 1.0 on the offset.
372 * This is a non-physical model of refraction but is useful on large refractive surfaces like water, since offsets have to stay small to avoid reading outside scene color.
373 */
374 RM_PixelNormalOffset UMETA(DisplayName="Pixel Normal Offset"),
375
376 /**
377 * By default, when the root node refraction pin is unplugged, no refraction will appear.
378 * Explicit 2D screen offset. This offset is independent of screen resolution and aspect ratio. The user is in charge of any strength and fading.
379 */
380 RM_2DOffset UMETA(DisplayName = "2D Offset"),
381
382 /**
383 * Refraction is disabled.
384 */
385 RM_None UMETA(DisplayName = "None"),
386};
387

403 RCM_CoverageAccountedFor UMETA(DisplayName = "Coverage Accounted For"),
404};

552/** Specifies which lighting channels are relevant */
553USTRUCT(BlueprintType)
554struct FLightingChannels
555{
556 GENERATED_BODY()
557
558 FLightingChannels() :
559 bChannel0(true),
560 bChannel1(false),
561 bChannel2(false)
562 {}
563
564 /** Default channel for all primitives and lights. */
565 UPROPERTY(EditAnywhere, BlueprintReadOnly, Category=Channels)
566 uint8 bChannel0:1;
567
568 /** First custom channel */
569 UPROPERTY(EditAnywhere, BlueprintReadOnly, Category=Channels)
570 uint8 bChannel1:1;
571
572 /** Second custom channel */
573 UPROPERTY(EditAnywhere, BlueprintReadOnly, Category=Channels)
574 uint8 bChannel2:1;
575};
576
577/** Converts lighting channels into a bitfield */
578inline uint8 GetLightingChannelMaskForStruct(FLightingChannels Value)
579{
580 // Note: this is packed into 3 bits of a stencil channel
581 return (uint8)((Value.bChannel0 ? 1 : 0) | (Value.bChannel1 << 1) | (Value.bChannel2 << 2));
582}
583
584/** Returns mask for only channel 0 */
585inline uint8 GetDefaultLightingChannelMask()
586{
587 return 1;
588}
589
590/** Returns the index of the first lighting channel set, or -1 if no channels are set. */
591inline int32 GetFirstLightingChannelFromMask(uint8 Mask)
592{
593 return Mask ? FPlatformMath::CountTrailingZeros(Mask) : -1;
594}

721
722/** Wrapper for a bitfield of shading models. A material contains one of these to describe what possible shading models can be used by that material. */
723USTRUCT()
724struct FMaterialShadingModelField
725{
726 GENERATED_USTRUCT_BODY()
727
728public:
729 FMaterialShadingModelField() {}
730 FMaterialShadingModelField(EMaterialShadingModel InShadingModel) { AddShadingModel(InShadingModel); }
731
732 void AddShadingModel(EMaterialShadingModel InShadingModel) { check(InShadingModel < MSM_NUM); ShadingModelField |= (1 << (uint16)InShadingModel); }
733 void RemoveShadingModel(EMaterialShadingModel InShadingModel) { ShadingModelField &= ~(1 << (uint16)InShadingModel); }
734 void ClearShadingModels() { ShadingModelField = 0; }
735
736 // Check if any of the given shading models are present
737 bool HasAnyShadingModel(const TArray<EMaterialShadingModel>& InShadingModels) const
738 {
739 for (EMaterialShadingModel ShadingModel : InShadingModels)
740 {
741 if (HasShadingModel(ShadingModel))
742 {
743 return true;
744 }
745 }
746 return false;
747 }
748
749 bool HasShadingModel(EMaterialShadingModel InShadingModel) const { return (ShadingModelField & (1 << (uint16)InShadingModel)) != 0; }
750 bool HasOnlyShadingModel(EMaterialShadingModel InShadingModel) const { return ShadingModelField == (1 << (uint16)InShadingModel); }
751 bool IsUnlit() const { return HasShadingModel(MSM_Unlit); }
752 bool IsLit() const { return !IsUnlit(); }
753 bool IsValid() const { return (ShadingModelField > 0) && (ShadingModelField < (1 << MSM_NUM)); }
754 uint16 GetShadingModelField() const { return ShadingModelField; }
755 void SetShadingModelField(uint16 InShadingModelField) { ShadingModelField = InShadingModelField; }
756 int32 CountShadingModels() const { return FMath::CountBits(ShadingModelField); }
757 EMaterialShadingModel GetFirstShadingModel() const { check(IsValid()); return (EMaterialShadingModel)FMath::CountTrailingZeros(ShadingModelField); }
758
759 bool operator==(const FMaterialShadingModelField& Other) const { return ShadingModelField == Other.GetShadingModelField(); }
760 bool operator!=(const FMaterialShadingModelField& Other) const { return ShadingModelField != Other.GetShadingModelField(); }
761
762private:
763 UPROPERTY()
764 uint16 ShadingModelField = 0;
765};

799/** Gather information from the Substrate material graph to setup material for runtime. */
800struct FSubstrateMaterialInfo
801{
802public:
803 FSubstrateMaterialInfo(bool bGatherGuids = false) { bGatherMaterialExpressionGuids = bGatherGuids; }
804 FSubstrateMaterialInfo(ESubstrateShadingModel InShadingModel) { AddShadingModel(InShadingModel); }
805
806 // Shading model
807 void AddShadingModel(ESubstrateShadingModel InShadingModel) { check(InShadingModel < SSM_NUM); ShadingModelField |= (1u << (uint32)InShadingModel); }
808 void SetSingleShadingModel(ESubstrateShadingModel InShadingModel) { check(InShadingModel < SSM_NUM); ShadingModelField = (1u << (uint32)InShadingModel); }
809 bool HasShadingModel(ESubstrateShadingModel InShadingModel) const { return (ShadingModelField & (1u << (uint32)InShadingModel)) != 0; }
810 bool HasOnlyShadingModel(ESubstrateShadingModel InShadingModel) const { return ShadingModelField == (1u << (uint32)InShadingModel); }
811 uint32 GetShadingModelField() const { return ShadingModelField; }
812 int32 CountShadingModels() const { return FMath::CountBits(ShadingModelField); }
813
814 // Subsurface profiles
815 void AddSubsurfaceProfile(USubsurfaceProfile* InProfile) { if (InProfile) SubsurfaceProfiles.Add(InProfile); }
816 int32 CountSubsurfaceProfiles() const { return SubsurfaceProfiles.Num(); }
817 USubsurfaceProfile* GetSubsurfaceProfile(int32 Index) const { return SubsurfaceProfiles.IsValidIndex(Index) ? SubsurfaceProfiles[Index] : nullptr; }
818
819 // Specular profiles
820 void AddSpecularProfile(USpecularProfile* InProfile) { if (InProfile) SpecularProfiles.Add(InProfile); }
821 int32 CountSpecularProfiles() const { return SpecularProfiles.Num(); }
822 USpecularProfile* GetSpecularProfile(int32 Index) const { return SpecularProfiles.IsValidIndex(Index) ? SpecularProfiles[Index] : nullptr; }
823
824 // Shading model from expression
825 void SetShadingModelFromExpression(bool bIn) { bHasShadingModelFromExpression = bIn ? 1u : 0u; }
826 bool HasShadingModelFromExpression() const { return bHasShadingModelFromExpression > 0u; }
827
828 // Substrate material expression GUIDs
829 void AddGuid(const FGuid& In) { if (bGatherMaterialExpressionGuids) { MaterialExpressionGuids.Add(In); } }
830 const TArray<FGuid>& GetGuids() const { return MaterialExpressionGuids; }
831
832 uint64 GetPropertyConnected() const { return ConnectedPropertyMask; }
833 void AddPropertyConnected(uint64 In) { ConnectedPropertyMask |= (1ull << In); }
834 bool HasPropertyConnected(uint64 In) const { return !!(ConnectedPropertyMask & (1ull << In)); }
835 static bool HasPropertyConnected(uint64 InConnectedPropertyMask, uint64 In) { return !!(InConnectedPropertyMask & (1ull << In)); }
836
837 bool IsValid() const { return (ShadingModelField > 0) && (ShadingModelField < (1 << SSM_NUM)); }
838
839 bool operator==(const FSubstrateMaterialInfo& Other) const { return ShadingModelField == Other.GetShadingModelField(); }
840 bool operator!=(const FSubstrateMaterialInfo& Other) const { return ShadingModelField != Other.GetShadingModelField(); }
841
842#if WITH_EDITOR
843 // Returns true if everything went fine (not out of Substrate tree stack)
844 bool PushSubstrateTreeStack()
845 {
846 bOutOfStackDepthWhenParsing = bOutOfStackDepthWhenParsing || (++ParsingStackDepth > SUBSTRATE_TREE_MAX_DEPTH);
847 return !bOutOfStackDepthWhenParsing;
848 }
849 void PopSubstrateTreeStack()
850 {
851 ParsingStackDepth--;
852 check(ParsingStackDepth >= 0);
853 }
854 bool GetSubstrateTreeOutOfStackDepthOccurred()
855 {
856 return bOutOfStackDepthWhenParsing;
857 }
858#endif
859
860private:
861 uint32 ShadingModelField = 0;
862
863 /* Indicates if the shading model is constant or data-driven from the shader graph */
864 uint8 bHasShadingModelFromExpression = 0;
865
866 /* Indicates which (legacy) inputs are connected */
867 uint64 ConnectedPropertyMask = 0;
868
869 TArray<TObjectPtr<USubsurfaceProfile>> SubsurfaceProfiles;
870
871 TArray<TObjectPtr<USpecularProfile>> SpecularProfiles;
872
873 /* Material expression GUIDs for all the traversed Substrate nodes */
874 bool bGatherMaterialExpressionGuids = false;
875 TArray<FGuid> MaterialExpressionGuids;
876
877#if WITH_EDITOR
878 // A simple way to detect and prevent node re-entry due to cycling graph; stop the compilation and avoid crashing.
879 bool bOutOfStackDepthWhenParsing = false;
880 int32 ParsingStackDepth = 0;
881#endif
882};

1535 /** Will not create any representation in the physics engine. Cannot be used for spatial queries (raycasts, sweeps, overlaps) or simulation (rigid body, constraints). Best performance possible (especially for moving objects) */

1537 /** Only used for spatial queries (raycasts, sweeps, and overlaps). Cannot be used for simulation (rigid body, constraints). Useful for character movement and things that do not need physical simulation. Performance gains by keeping data out of simulation tree. */

1539 /** Only used only for physics simulation (rigid body, constraints). Cannot be used for spatial queries (raycasts, sweeps, overlaps). Useful for jiggly bits on characters that do not need per bone detection. Performance gains by keeping data out of query tree */
1540 PhysicsOnly UMETA(DisplayName="Physics Only (No Query Collision)"),
1541 /** Can be used for both spatial queries (raycasts, sweeps, overlaps) and simulation (rigid body, constraints). */
1542 QueryAndPhysics UMETA(DisplayName="Collision Enabled (Query and Physics)"),
1543 /** Only used for probing the physics simulation (rigid body, constraints). Cannot be used for spatial queries (raycasts,
1544 sweeps, overlaps). Useful for when you want to detect potential physics interactions and pass contact data to hit callbacks
1545 or contact modification, but don't want to physically react to these contacts. */
1546 ProbeOnly UMETA(DisplayName="Probe Only (Contact Data, No Query or Physics Collision)"),
1547 /** Can be used for both spatial queries (raycasts, sweeps, overlaps) and probing the physics simulation (rigid body,
1548 constraints). Will not allow for actual physics interaction, but will generate contact data, trigger hit callbacks, and
1549 contacts will appear in contact modification. */
1550 QueryAndProbe UMETA(DisplayName="Query and Probe (Query Collision and Contact Data, No Physics Collision)")

1592
1593FORCEINLINE ECollisionEnabled::Type CollisionEnabledIntersection(ECollisionEnabled::Type CollisionEnabledA, ECollisionEnabled::Type CollisionEnabledB)
1594{
1595 // Combine collision two enabled data.
1596 //
1597 // The intersection follows the following rules:
1598 //
1599 // * For the result to have Query, both data must have Query
1600 // * For the result to have Probe, either data must have Probe
1601 // * For the result to have Physics, both data must have Physics and the result must not have Probe
1602 //
1603 // This way if an object is query-only, for example, but one of its shapes is query-and-physics,
1604 // the object's settings win and the shape ends up being query-only. And if the object is marked
1605 // as physics, but the child is marked as probe (or vice versa), use probe.
1606 //
1607 // The following matrix represents the intersection relationship.
1608 // NOTE: The order of types must match the order declared in ECollisionEnabled!
1609 using namespace ECollisionEnabled;
1610 static constexpr ECollisionEnabled::Type IntersectionMatrix[5][5] = {
1611 /* | QueryOnly PhysicsOnly QueryAndPhysics ProbeOnly QueryAndProbe */
1612 /*-----------------+------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
1613 /* QueryOnly | */ { QueryOnly, NoCollision, QueryOnly, NoCollision, QueryOnly },
1614 /* PhysicsOnly | */ { NoCollision, PhysicsOnly, PhysicsOnly, ProbeOnly, ProbeOnly },
1615 /* QueryAndPhysics | */ { QueryOnly, PhysicsOnly, QueryAndPhysics, ProbeOnly, QueryAndProbe },
1616 /* ProbeOnly | */ { NoCollision, ProbeOnly, ProbeOnly, ProbeOnly, ProbeOnly },
1617 /* QueryAndProbe | */ { QueryOnly, ProbeOnly, QueryAndProbe, ProbeOnly, QueryAndProbe }
1618 };
1619
1620 // Subtract 1 because the first index is NoCollision.
1621 // If both indices indicate _some_ collision setting (ie, greater than -1),
1622 // lookup their intersection setting in the matrix.
1623 const int32 IndexA = (int32)CollisionEnabledA - 1;
1624 const int32 IndexB = (int32)CollisionEnabledB - 1;
1625 if (IndexA >= 0 && IndexB >= 0)
1626 {
1627 return IntersectionMatrix[IndexA][IndexB];
1628 }
1629
1630 // Either of the two settings were set to NoCollision which trumps all
1631 return ECollisionEnabled::NoCollision;
1632}
1633
1634/** Convert a set of three bools into an ECollisionEnabled */
1635FORCEINLINE ECollisionEnabled::Type CollisionEnabledFromFlags(const bool bQuery, const bool bPhysics, const bool bProbe)
1636{
1637 // Convert to ints for bit manipulation
1638 const int32 QueryBit = static_cast<uint32>(bQuery);
1639 const int32 PhysicsBit = static_cast<uint32>(bPhysics);
1640 const int32 ProbeBit = static_cast<uint32>(bProbe);
1641
1642 // NOTE:
1643 // We use &~ between physics and probe because we cannot have a case with
1644 // both enabled, and in every case probe "beats" physics. See the collision
1645 // type rules outlined in the comments in CollisionEnabledIntersection.
1646 //
1647 // index type bits: probe/physics/query
1648 // ----------------------------------------------------
1649 // 0 NoCollision 000
1650 // 1 QueryOnly 001
1651 // 2 PhysicsOnly 010
1652 // 3 QueryAndPhysics 011
1653 // 4 ProbeOnly 100 (& 110)
1654 // 5 QueryAndProbe 101 (& 111)
1655 return static_cast<ECollisionEnabled::Type>(
1656 (QueryBit << 0) |
1657 (PhysicsBit & (~ProbeBit)) << 1 |
1658 (ProbeBit << 2));
1659}
1660
1661/** Convert an ECollisionEnabled enum into a set of three bools */
1662FORCEINLINE void CollisionEnabledToFlags(const ECollisionEnabled::Type CollisionEnabled, bool& bQuery, bool& bPhysics, bool& bProbe)
1663{
1664 const int32 Bits = static_cast<int32>(CollisionEnabled);
1665 bQuery = ((Bits & 0x1) != 0);
1666 bPhysics = ((Bits & 0x2) != 0);
1667 bProbe = ((Bits & 0x4) != 0);
1668}

1914/** Struct for caching Quat<->Rotator conversions. */
1915struct FRotationConversionCache
1916{
1917 FRotationConversionCache()
1918 {
1919 }
1920
1921 /** Convert a FRotator to FQuat. Uses the cached conversion if possible, and updates it if there was no match. */
1922 FORCEINLINE_DEBUGGABLE FQuat RotatorToQuat(const FRotator& InRotator) const
1923 {
1924 FPayload& Payload = GetOrCreatePayload();
1925 if (LIKELY(Payload.CachedRotator != InRotator))
1926 {
1927 Payload.CachedRotator = InRotator.GetNormalized();
1928 Payload.CachedQuat = Payload.CachedRotator.Quaternion();
1929 }
1930 return Payload.CachedQuat;
1931 }
1932
1933 /** Convert a FRotator to FQuat. Uses the cached conversion if possible, but does *NOT* update the cache if there was no match. */
1934 FORCEINLINE_DEBUGGABLE FQuat RotatorToQuat_ReadOnly(const FRotator& InRotator) const
1935 {
1936 if (LIKELY(PayloadPtr.IsValid()))
1937 {
1938 FPayload& Payload = *PayloadPtr;
1939 if (LIKELY(Payload.CachedRotator == InRotator))
1940 {
1941 return Payload.CachedQuat;
1942 }
1943 }
1944 return InRotator.Quaternion();
1945 }
1946
1947 /** Convert a FQuat to FRotator. Uses the cached conversion if possible, and updates it if there was no match. */
1948 FORCEINLINE_DEBUGGABLE FRotator QuatToRotator(const FQuat& InQuat) const
1949 {
1950 FPayload& Payload = GetOrCreatePayload();
1951 if (LIKELY(Payload.CachedQuat != InQuat))
1952 {
1953 Payload.CachedQuat = InQuat.GetNormalized();
1954 Payload.CachedRotator = Payload.CachedQuat.Rotator();
1955 }
1956 return Payload.CachedRotator;
1957 }
1958
1959 /** Convert a FQuat to FRotator. Uses the cached conversion if possible, but does *NOT* update the cache if there was no match. */
1960 FORCEINLINE_DEBUGGABLE FRotator QuatToRotator_ReadOnly(const FQuat& InQuat) const
1961 {
1962 if (LIKELY(PayloadPtr.IsValid()))
1963 {
1964 FPayload& Payload = *PayloadPtr;
1965 if (LIKELY(Payload.CachedQuat == InQuat))
1966 {
1967 return Payload.CachedRotator;
1968 }
1969 }
1970 return InQuat.GetNormalized().Rotator();
1971 }
1972
1973 /** Version of QuatToRotator when the Quat is known to already be normalized. */
1974 FORCEINLINE_DEBUGGABLE FRotator NormalizedQuatToRotator(const FQuat& InNormalizedQuat) const
1975 {
1976 FPayload& Payload = GetOrCreatePayload();
1977 if (LIKELY(Payload.CachedQuat != InNormalizedQuat))
1978 {
1979 Payload.CachedQuat = InNormalizedQuat;
1980 Payload.CachedRotator = InNormalizedQuat.Rotator();
1981 }
1982 return Payload.CachedRotator;
1983 }
1984
1985 /** Version of QuatToRotator when the Quat is known to already be normalized. Does *NOT* update the cache if there was no match. */
1986 FORCEINLINE_DEBUGGABLE FRotator NormalizedQuatToRotator_ReadOnly(const FQuat& InNormalizedQuat) const
1987 {
1988 if (LIKELY(PayloadPtr.IsValid()))
1989 {
1990 FPayload& Payload = *PayloadPtr;
1991 if (LIKELY(Payload.CachedQuat == InNormalizedQuat))
1992 {
1993 return Payload.CachedRotator;
1994 }
1995 }
1996 return InNormalizedQuat.Rotator();
1997 }
1998
1999 /** Return the cached Quat. */
2000 FORCEINLINE_DEBUGGABLE FQuat GetCachedQuat() const
2001 {
2002 if (UNLIKELY(!PayloadPtr.IsValid()))
2003 {
2004 return FQuat::Identity;
2005 }
2006 return PayloadPtr->CachedQuat;
2007 }
2008
2009 /** Return the cached Rotator. */
2010 FORCEINLINE_DEBUGGABLE FRotator GetCachedRotator() const
2011 {
2012 if (UNLIKELY(!PayloadPtr.IsValid()))
2013 {
2014 return FRotator::ZeroRotator;
2015 }
2016 return PayloadPtr->CachedRotator;
2017 }
2018
2019 FRotationConversionCache& operator=(const FRotationConversionCache& Other)
2020 {
2021 if (LIKELY(PayloadPtr.IsValid() || Other.PayloadPtr.IsValid()))
2022 {
2023 FPayload& Payload = GetOrCreatePayload();
2024 Payload.CachedQuat = Other.GetCachedQuat();
2025 Payload.CachedRotator = Other.GetCachedRotator();
2026 }
2027 return *this;
2028 }
2029
2030private:
2031
2032 struct FPayload
2033 {
2034 mutable FQuat CachedQuat; // FQuat matching CachedRotator such that CachedQuat.Rotator() == CachedRotator.
2035 mutable FRotator CachedRotator; // FRotator matching CachedQuat such that CachedRotator.Quaternion() == CachedQuat.
2036
2037 FPayload()
2038 : CachedQuat(FQuat::Identity)
2039 , CachedRotator(FRotator::ZeroRotator)
2040 {}
2041 };
2042
2043 inline FPayload& GetOrCreatePayload() const
2044 {
2045 if (UNLIKELY(!PayloadPtr.IsValid()))
2046 {
2047 PayloadPtr = MakeUnique<FPayload>();
2048 }
2049 return *PayloadPtr;
2050 }
2051
2052 mutable TUniquePtr<FPayload> PayloadPtr;
2053};

2560 * @param : bNewInterpSkippedFrames. When skipping a frame, should it be interpolated or frozen?

2602 float GetTimeAdjustment()

2609 {
2610 if (OptimizeMode == TrailMode)

3429/** Struct allowing control over "walkable" normals, by allowing a restriction or relaxation of what steepness is normally walkable. */
3430USTRUCT(BlueprintType)
3431struct FWalkableSlopeOverride
3432{
3433 GENERATED_BODY()
3434
3435 /**
3436 * Behavior of this surface (whether we affect the walkable slope).
3437 * @see GetWalkableSlopeBehavior(), SetWalkableSlopeBehavior()
3438 */
3439 UPROPERTY(EditAnywhere, BlueprintReadWrite, Category=WalkableSlopeOverride)
3440 TEnumAsByte<EWalkableSlopeBehavior> WalkableSlopeBehavior;
3441
3442 /**
3443 * Override walkable slope angle (in degrees), applying the rules of the Walkable Slope Behavior.
3444 * @see GetWalkableSlopeAngle(), SetWalkableSlopeAngle()
3445 */
3446 UPROPERTY(EditAnywhere, BlueprintReadWrite, Category=WalkableSlopeOverride, meta=(ClampMin="0", ClampMax="90", UIMin="0", UIMax="90"))
3447 float WalkableSlopeAngle;
3448
3449private:
3450
3451 // Cached angle for which we computed a cosine.
3452 mutable float CachedSlopeAngle;
3453 // Cached cosine of angle.
3454 mutable float CachedSlopeCos;
3455
3456public:
3457
3458 FWalkableSlopeOverride()
3459 : WalkableSlopeBehavior(WalkableSlope_Default)
3460 , WalkableSlopeAngle(0.f)
3461 , CachedSlopeAngle(0.f)
3462 , CachedSlopeCos(1.f)
3463 { }
3464
3465 FWalkableSlopeOverride(EWalkableSlopeBehavior NewSlopeBehavior, float NewSlopeAngle)
3466 : WalkableSlopeBehavior(NewSlopeBehavior)
3467 , WalkableSlopeAngle(NewSlopeAngle)
3468 , CachedSlopeAngle(0.f)
3469 , CachedSlopeCos(1.f)
3470 {
3471 }
3472
3473 /** Gets the slope override behavior. */
3474 FORCEINLINE EWalkableSlopeBehavior GetWalkableSlopeBehavior() const
3475 {
3476 return WalkableSlopeBehavior;
3477 }
3478
3479 /** Gets the slope angle used for the override behavior. */
3480 FORCEINLINE float GetWalkableSlopeAngle() const
3481 {
3482 return WalkableSlopeAngle;
3483 }
3484
3485 /** Set the slope override behavior. */
3486 FORCEINLINE void SetWalkableSlopeBehavior(EWalkableSlopeBehavior NewSlopeBehavior)
3487 {
3488 WalkableSlopeBehavior = NewSlopeBehavior;
3489 }
3490
3491 /** Set the slope angle used for the override behavior. */
3492 FORCEINLINE void SetWalkableSlopeAngle(float NewSlopeAngle)
3493 {
3494 WalkableSlopeAngle = FMath::Clamp(NewSlopeAngle, 0.f, 90.f);
3495 }
3496
3497 /** Given a walkable floor normal Z value, either relax or restrict the value if we override such behavior. */
3498 float ModifyWalkableFloorZ(float InWalkableFloorZ) const
3499 {
3500 switch(WalkableSlopeBehavior)
3501 {
3502 case WalkableSlope_Default:
3503 {
3504 return InWalkableFloorZ;
3505 }
3506
3507 case WalkableSlope_Increase:
3508 {
3509 CheckCachedData();
3510 return FMath::Min(InWalkableFloorZ, CachedSlopeCos);
3511 }
3512
3513 case WalkableSlope_Decrease:
3514 {
3515 CheckCachedData();
3516 return FMath::Max(InWalkableFloorZ, CachedSlopeCos);
3517 }
3518
3519 case WalkableSlope_Unwalkable:
3520 {
3521 // Z component of a normal will always be less than this, so this will be unwalkable.
3522 return 2.0f;
3523 }
3524
3525 case WalkableSlope_Max:
3526 default:
3527 {
3528 return InWalkableFloorZ;
3529 }
3530 }
3531 }
3532
3533private:
3534
3535 void CheckCachedData() const
3536 {
3537 if (CachedSlopeAngle != WalkableSlopeAngle)
3538 {
3539 const float AngleRads = FMath::DegreesToRadians(WalkableSlopeAngle);
3540 CachedSlopeCos = FMath::Clamp(FMath::Cos(AngleRads), 0.f, 1.f);
3541 CachedSlopeAngle = WalkableSlopeAngle;
3542 }
3543 }
3544};

3873/**
3874 * Structure for recording float values and displaying them as an Histogram through DrawDebugFloatHistory.
3875 */
3876USTRUCT(BlueprintType)
3877struct FDebugFloatHistory
3878{
3879 GENERATED_BODY()
3880
3881private:
3882 /** Samples */
3883 UPROPERTY(Transient)
3884 TArray<float> Samples;
3885
3886public:
3887 /** Max Samples to record. */
3888 UPROPERTY(EditAnywhere, BlueprintReadWrite, Category="DebugFloatHistory")
3889 int32 MaxSamples;
3890
3891 /** Min value to record. */
3892 UPROPERTY(EditAnywhere, BlueprintReadWrite, Category = "DebugFloatHistory")
3893 float MinValue;
3894
3895 /** Max value to record. */
3896 UPROPERTY(EditAnywhere, BlueprintReadWrite, Category = "DebugFloatHistory")
3897 float MaxValue;
3898
3899 /** Auto adjust Min/Max as new values are recorded? */
3900 UPROPERTY(EditAnywhere, BlueprintReadWrite, Category = "DebugFloatHistory")
3901 bool bAutoAdjustMinMax;
3902
3903 FDebugFloatHistory()
3904 : MaxSamples(100)
3905 , MinValue(0.f)
3906 , MaxValue(0.f)
3907 , bAutoAdjustMinMax(true)
3908 { }
3909
3910 FDebugFloatHistory(int32 const & InMaxSamples, float const & InMinValue, float const & InMaxValue, bool const & InbAutoAdjustMinMax)
3911 : MaxSamples(InMaxSamples)
3912 , MinValue(InMinValue)
3913 , MaxValue(InMaxValue)
3914 , bAutoAdjustMinMax(InbAutoAdjustMinMax)
3915 { }
3916
3917 /**
3918 * Record a new Sample.
3919 * if bAutoAdjustMinMax is true, this new value will potentially adjust those bounds.
3920 * Otherwise value will be clamped before being recorded.
3921 * If MaxSamples is exceeded, old values will be deleted.
3922 * @param FloatValue new sample to record.
3923 */
3924 void AddSample(float const & FloatValue)
3925 {
3926 if (bAutoAdjustMinMax)
3927 {
3928 // Adjust bounds and record value.
3929 MinValue = FMath::Min(MinValue, FloatValue);
3930 MaxValue = FMath::Max(MaxValue, FloatValue);
3931 Samples.Insert(FloatValue, 0);
3932 }
3933 else
3934 {
3935 // Record clamped value.
3936 Samples.Insert(FMath::Clamp(FloatValue, MinValue, MaxValue), 0);
3937 }
3938
3939 // Do not exceed MaxSamples recorded.
3940 if( Samples.Num() > MaxSamples )
3941 {
3942 Samples.RemoveAt(MaxSamples, Samples.Num() - MaxSamples);
3943 }
3944 }
3945
3946 /** Range between Min and Max values */
3947 float GetMinMaxRange() const
3948 {
3949 return (MaxValue - MinValue);
3950 }
3951
3952 /** Min value. This could either be the min value recorded or min value allowed depending on 'bAutoAdjustMinMax'. */
3953 float GetMinValue() const
3954 {
3955 return MinValue;
3956 }
3957
3958 /** Max value. This could be either the max value recorded or max value allowed depending on 'bAutoAdjustMinMax'. */
3959 float GetMaxValue() const
3960 {
3961 return MaxValue;
3962 }
3963
3964 /** Number of Samples currently recorded */
3965 int GetNumSamples() const
3966 {
3967 return Samples.Num();
3968 }
3969
3970 /** Read access to Samples array */
3971 TArray<float> const & GetSamples() const
3972 {
3973 return Samples;
3974 }
3975};
